    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-04-08T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-04-08T05:00:00-05:00" n="358"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d358">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.114 Reidun/112: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Biddle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Oslo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-08T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 8, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 9—4:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Department’s telegram No. 8, March 26, 6 p.m. and Legation despatch No. 148,
                    March 28<note n="59" xml:id="d358fn59">Latter not printed.</note> regarding
                    seizure of steamship <hi rend="italic">Reidun.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Acting Foreign Minister Aubert in exposition 1 hour’s duration yesterday
                    reiterated with emphasis his remarks of March 25 concerning belief in illegal
                    nature of action of the American authorities. He considered that Norwegian
                    rights under treaty may have been infringed and that in a conflict between
                    domestic law and international treaty, the Department of State should uphold
                    treaty’s primacy against local authorities and insist that steamship <hi
                        rend="italic">Reidun</hi> and officers should be treated as property and
                    subjects of a treaty nation.</p>
                <p>Despatch will be forwarded.<note n="60" xml:id="d358fn60">No. 156, April 8: not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Biddle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
